# Karpathy 4 Principles (MANDATORY)

These principles apply to EVERY code change you make:

## 1. Think Before Coding
- State your assumptions BEFORE writing code
- Present 2-3 tradeoffs when multiple approaches exist
- If confused → STOP and ask, don't guess
- Understand the "why" before the "how"

## 2. Simplicity First
- Write the MINIMUM code that solves the problem
- No speculative features ("might need later")
- No single-use abstractions
- If you can delete code instead of adding code → delete
- Prefer standard library over external dependency

## 3. Surgical Changes
- Touch ONLY what the user's request requires
- Don't "improve" adjacent code while you're there
- Every changed line must trace back to the user's request
- If you see something else that needs fixing → mention it, don't fix it

## 4. Goal-Driven Execution
- Define success criteria BEFORE starting
- Write tests first (TDD when practical)
- Loop until verified: code → test → refine
- Evidence over claims — run the code, don't just say it works

